<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-section-limit-definitions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Limit Definitions</title>
  <p>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x)</m> be a function defined on an open interval containing <m>a</m>, except possibly at <m>a</m> itself
        and <m>L</m> be any real number.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <definition xml:id="def_two_sided_limit">
      <p>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> is <m>L</m>, i.e.
            <me>\lim_{{x \to a}} f(x) = L</me>
            if for every number <m>\epsilon \gt 0</m> there exists a number <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that:
            <me>0 \lt |x - a| \lt \delta \implies |f(x) - L| \lt \epsilon</me>
            or equivalently:
            <me>a - \delta \lt x \lt a + \delta \implies L - \epsilon \lt f(x) \lt L + \epsilon</me>
            "The limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> is <m>L</m>" means the limit exists
            and is equal to the real number <m>L</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </p>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        <xref ref="def_two_sided_limit"/> says the distance between <m>f(x)</m> and <m>L</m> can be made arbitrarily small
        (<m>\epsilon</m>-small) by making the distance from <m>x</m> to <m>a</m> sufficiently small (<m>\delta</m>-small).
        Or, in terms of intervals, <m>f(x)</m> is guaranteed to be in the open interval <m>(L - \epsilon, L + \epsilon)</m>
        if <m>x</m> is in the open interval <m>(a - \delta, a + \delta)</m> where <m>x \neq a</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <definition xml:id="def_left_hand_limit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the left is <m>L</m>, i.e.
          <me>\lim_{{x \to a^-}} f(x) = L</me>
          if for every number <m>\epsilon \gt 0</m> there exists a number <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that:
          <me>a - \delta \lt x \lt a \implies L - \epsilon \lt f(x) \lt L + \epsilon</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def_right_hand_limit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> from the right is <m>L</m>, i.e.
          <me>\lim_{{x \to a^+}} f(x) = L</me>
          if for every number <m>\epsilon \gt 0</m> there exists a number <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that:
          <me>a \lt x \lt a + \delta \implies L - \epsilon \lt f(x) \lt L + \epsilon</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <definition xml:id="def_infinite_limit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> is infinity, i.e.
          <me>\lim_{{x \to a}} f(x) = \infty</me>
          if for every positive number <m>M</m> there exists a number <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that:
          <me>0 \lt |x - a| \lt \delta \implies f(x) \gt M</me>
          The limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> is negative infinity, i.e. 
          <me>\lim_{{x \to a}} f(x) = -\infty</me> 
          if for every negative number <m>N</m> there exists a number <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that:
          <me>0 \lt |x - a| \lt \delta \implies f(x) \lt N</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <p>
        <xref ref="def_infinite_limit"/> says that given any arbitrarily large positive number <m>M</m>,
        you can find an even bigger value for <m>f(x)</m> if <m>x</m> is sufficiently close to <m>a</m>.
        Conversely, given any arbitrarily large negative number <m>N</m>,
        you can find an even more negative value for <m>f(x)</m> if <m>x</m> is sufficiently close to <m>a</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <definition xml:id="def_vertical_asymptote">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The line <m>x = a</m> is called a <alert>vertical asymptote</alert> of the curve <m>y = f(x)</m>
          if at least one of the following is true:
          <md>
            <mrow>\lim_{{x \to a}} f(x) \amp = \infty \amp \lim_{{x \to a^-}} f(x) \amp = \infty \amp \lim_{{x \to a^+}} f(x) \amp = \infty</mrow>
            <mrow>\lim_{{x \to a}} f(x) \amp = -\infty \amp \lim_{{x \to a^-}} f(x) \amp = -\infty \amp \lim_{{x \to a^+}} f(x) \amp = -\infty</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </p>
</section>
